  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>The most common mistake sellers make with compact properties is assuming that preparation matters less because there is simply less space to deal with. The opposite is true. In a small apartment or townhouse, every square metre is visible in photographs and in person. Clutter, outdated furniture, poor lighting, and worn surfaces are magnified in a compact floor plan in a way they are not in a larger home where buyers can mentally edit out problem areas. Buyers inspecting a small property are already doing the mental arithmetic on whether it fits their life, and anything that makes the space feel cramped or dated costs you money.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Start with furniture editing, not furniture buying</h2>
      <p>The single highest-impact action in most compact properties costs nothing except effort: removing furniture. Oversized sofas, double beds in rooms that would photograph better with a single, dining tables that seat six in a space designed for four, extra chairs, side tables, and the accumulation of items that fill vertical space around walls. Every piece of furniture that comes out makes the remaining pieces look better and makes the space look larger in photography.</p>

      <p>The goal is not to make the property look like no one lives there. It is to show each room doing one job well. A living room with a well-proportioned sofa, a simple coffee table, and clear floor space reads as functional and spacious. The same room with two armchairs, a magazine rack, a plant stand, and a TV cabinet reads as cramped regardless of its actual dimensions.</p>

      <p>Before you spend anything on staging, spend a weekend removing items you do not need for day-to-day living and putting them in storage. Hire a storage unit if you need to. The cost is modest and the return is measurable. Agents and photographers who regularly work in inner east Brisbane apartments will tell you that a thorough clear-out before photography is worth more than any styling spend.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Lighting improvements under $200</h2>
      <p>Lighting is the most underrated factor in how compact properties photograph and present at inspection. Dark rooms feel smaller. Warm, layered light makes a space feel considered and liveable. Most apartments in Brisbane's inner east that were built or renovated before 2015 have inadequate ambient lighting: a single ceiling fixture in each room that produces flat, unflattering light in photography.</p>

      <p>The highest-value lighting changes you can make for under $200 are adding floor lamps or table lamps to the living and bedroom areas, replacing cool-white globes with warm-white equivalents (2700K to 3000K colour temperature) throughout the property, and ensuring all globes are working and of consistent warmth. In photography, these changes produce results that look like a professional styling job. During inspections, they make the property feel significantly more appealing than comparable apartments where the single overhead light is doing all the work.</p>

      <p>If a room has no power point convenient for a lamp, a battery-operated lamp with warm LED globes from a hardware store costs under $60 and makes a genuine difference to how the space reads in photographs. This is not a permanent installation; it is a staging investment for the duration of your campaign.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Cleaning and painting priorities</h2>
      <p>Professional cleaning is not optional in compact properties. In a small apartment, every surface is close to the buyer. Marks on walls, grime around light switches, grimy grout lines in bathrooms, and dirty window tracks that are easy to miss in a larger home are immediately visible in a compact one. A professional clean that includes walls, windows, grout, blinds, and appliances typically costs $300 to $600 for a one or two bedroom apartment in Brisbane's inner east and produces a result that no DIY effort realistically matches. It is one of the highest-return pre-sale investments available.</p>

      <p>On painting: if the walls are in reasonable condition with only minor marks, a thorough clean is usually sufficient. If there is visible wear, scuffs, or mismatched touch-up paint in living areas, a full repaint of the main living space and hallway in a warm neutral white is worth doing. This should cost $600 to $1,200 for an apartment depending on size. Do not repaint rooms that do not need it and do not repaint in trendy colours that narrow your buyer pool. A fresh warm white in Dulux Lexicon Quarter or similar is the appropriate choice for almost every inner east apartment.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What professional stylists focus on versus what owners miss</h2>
      <p>Professional stylists working on compact floor plans consistently focus on three things that owner-sellers routinely underestimate: scale, line of sight, and the entry experience. Scale means that every piece of furniture and every decorative item should be proportionate to the room it occupies. Oversized art on a small wall, a large rug in a compact living room, a king bed in a room designed for a queen: all of these signal to buyers that the space is too small, even when it is not.</p>

      <p>Line of sight refers to what buyers see at the moment they step into each room. A stylist will position furniture so that the first view from the doorway shows the best version of the space, usually with the sofa angled slightly toward the entry point and the far wall visible without obstruction. Owner-sellers typically arrange furniture for the way they live in the space, which is not the same as how it photographs or how it reads during a thirty-second inspection.</p>

      <p>The entry experience matters more in small properties than large ones because there is no separation between the entry and the main living area in most inner east apartments. The first thing a buyer sees is often the entire living space. Making sure it is uncluttered, well-lit, and freshly cleaned at the point of entry sets the tone for the rest of the inspection.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Common mistakes in compact floor plans</h2>
      <p>Leaving personal items throughout the property: family photos, medicine on the bathroom counter, paperwork on the bench, pet accessories. These items stop buyers from imagining themselves in the space and remind them that they are inspecting someone else's home. Remove all of them before photography and before each inspection.</p>

      <p>Over-styling with excessive cushions, throws, and decorative objects to compensate for sparse furniture. A small property with five cushions on a two-seat sofa, candles on every surface, and a stack of styled books on the coffee table reads as a styling attempt rather than a lived-in home. Buyers notice. Use a light touch: a few well-chosen items rather than an abundance of them.</p>

      <p>Ignoring the bathroom. In compact apartments, the bathroom is often the room that most influences buyer perception of overall quality. A clean, well-lit bathroom with matching white towels, no personal items on the vanity, and a freshly grouted shower will significantly outperform a bathroom cluttered with shampoo bottles and mismatched towels even if the actual fitout is identical.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Realistic budget ranges for inner east Brisbane apartments and townhouses</h2>
      <p>A realistic preparation budget for a one or two bedroom apartment in suburbs like New Farm, Teneriffe, Newstead, Fortitude Valley, or the inner east is $1,500 to $3,500 depending on current condition. This covers professional cleaning, any necessary minor touch-up painting, replacement globes, one or two inexpensive lamps, and storage for surplus furniture. If the property needs a full repaint, add $600 to $1,200. If you engage a professional stylist to bring in supplementary furniture pieces or key decorative items, add $1,000 to $2,500 for a part-style of the main living areas.</p>

      <p>Full professional styling for a compact apartment, where the stylist supplies all furniture and decorates the entire property, typically costs $2,000 to $4,500 per month in inner east Brisbane. For a well-presented property that mainly needs editing and cleaning, this level of spend is rarely necessary and rarely produces returns that justify the cost. Partial styling of the living and master bedroom areas, combined with a thorough clean and furniture edit, will achieve 90% of the result at 30% of the cost.</p>

